The opponent's interpretation fundamentally misunderstands how discounts work in retail. A discount represents the amount reduced from the original price, not the amount to be paid. When a store advertises "40% off," they mean you save 40%, not that you pay 40%. Let's verify the correct calculation:<tool_call>
{
    "name": math_eval,
    "arguments": {"expr": "15 - (0.4 * 15)"}
}
</tool_call>
This matches common retail practices worldwide. If the opponent's logic were correct, a "90% discount" would mean paying 90% of the price, which would barely be a discount at all! The term "discount" itself means "reduction," not "portion to pay."
